{{! ----- Annotations ----- }}
<section id="feature-annotations">
<h3>PDF / image annotation</h3>

<p>Annotation is built on <strong>PDF.js</strong> v4.10 (rendering) and
<strong>Fabric.js</strong> v6.9 (the interactive overlay). Both libraries
ship bundled with the plugin under <code>thirdparty/</code>; no CDN
dependency.</p>

<h4>What you can do</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Comment pins</strong> — drop a pin and attach hover-revealed text.</li>
    <li><strong>Stamps</strong> — preset rubber-stamp graphics (tick, cross, etc.).</li>
    <li><strong>Freehand pencil</strong> with adjustable width and colour.</li>
    <li><strong>Text annotations</strong> placed directly on the page.</li>
    <li><strong>Shapes</strong> — rectangle and circle outlines/fills.</li>
    <li><strong>Area highlight</strong> — drag a translucent box over any region (charts, diagrams, whitespace) where text selection won't reach.</li>
    <li><strong>Text highlight &amp; strikethrough</strong> — select the text itself, the way any PDF reader works, and on release each visual line of the selection becomes a translucent highlight box or a thin strike-through line. The colour picker drives both (yellow for the classic highlighter look, red for strikethrough). Per-line shapes group so the whole mark selects, drags, and deletes as one unit; resize and rotate are locked because the geometry is bound to the underlying words, while drag stays enabled for nudging.</li>
    <li><strong>Eraser</strong> for individual annotations.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Per-page state</h4>
<p>Annotations are stored per page as a Fabric.js JSON snapshot
(<code>local_unifiedgrader_annot</code> table, keyed on
<code>cmid + userid + fileid + pagenum</code>). Switching pages saves the
current page's state and loads the next.</p>

<h4>Flattened annotated PDF</h4>
<p>When the teacher saves annotations, the plugin flattens them into a
real PDF using <strong>pdf-lib</strong> (also bundled). The flattened PDF
is uploaded via web service and stored in the
<code>local_unifiedgrader/annotatedpdf</code> filearea. Students view it
through the feedback banner; teachers can also download it from the
preview pane's right-rail.</p>

<p>The interactive viewer always shows the <em>original</em> PDF with the
Fabric.js overlay (so comments are still hover-revealable). The flattened
copy is only used for download.</p>

