{{! ----- Rich feedback ----- }}
<section id="feature-feedback">
<h3>Rich feedback (TinyMCE + recordings)</h3>

<p>The feedback editor is Moodle's preferred TinyMCE configuration. It is
initialised once on page load and reused across student switches via
<code>editor.setContent()</code> — much faster than destroying and
recreating the editor every time.</p>

<h4>Recording in the editor</h4>
<p>The TinyMCE <em>RecordRTC</em> plugin (or the SATS recorder TinyMCE
plugin if installed) is supported, so teachers can record audio or video
feedback inline. Recorded clips are uploaded to the editor's draft area
and end up in the standard <code>assignfeedback_comments</code> filearea
on save.</p>

<h4>Draft area lifecycle</h4>
<p>One draft area is allocated per page load and reused across student
switches. Critical detail: <code>file_prepare_draft_area()</code> only
copies files when the draftitemid is <em>empty</em>. To swap students
correctly the plugin manually copies files via
<code>create_file_from_storedfile()</code> and rewrites
<code>@@PLUGINFILE@@</code> tokens with
<code>file_rewrite_pluginfile_urls()</code>.</p>

<h4>Student feedback view</h4>
<p>Students read feedback through <code>view_feedback.php</code>. For
non-assignment activity types this serves a dedicated layout (e.g.
<code>feedback_view_quiz.mustache</code>) so the student sees their
attempt or posts alongside the marker's commentary.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Comment library ----- }}
<section id="feature-comment-library">
<h3>Comment library</h3>

<p>A library of canned feedback comments with tags. Each comment falls into
one of these scopes:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Personal</strong> — visible only to the marker who created them.</li>
    <li><strong>Course-scoped</strong> — automatically scoped via a regex extracting a course code from the course shortname (admin setting <code>coursecode_regex</code>).</li>
    <li><strong>Universal</strong> — your own comments with an empty course code, visible across every course you grade. Tick <em>Universal</em> on the new / edit form; a dedicated <em>Universal</em> sidebar bucket surfaces them and their tags appear in every course's pill row.</li>
    <li><strong>Shared</strong> — visible to other markers, with optional import to make a personal copy.</li>
    <li><strong>System defaults</strong> — curated by a manager and visible read-only to every teacher in every course. They carry a yellow star badge and live in their own <em>System defaults</em> sidebar bucket (see below).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Where it shows up</h4>
<ul>
    <li>A popout next to each marking-guide / rubric remark textarea.</li>
    <li>A popout when annotating PDFs (attaches to the active comment pin).</li>
    <li>An autocomplete suggester in marking-guide remark textareas (start typing to see matching library entries).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Finding comments</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Tag pills</strong> at the top of the popout filter the list. The pill row shows only system-default tags plus tags actually attached to a comment in the <em>current</em> course (or to a universal comment) — not every tag you have ever created.</li>
    <li><strong>Search box</strong> in the manage-library toolbar — case-insensitive substring match on comment text, combined with the active course and tag filters.</li>
    <li>Comments can carry multiple tags; manage them from the <em>Manage</em> link in the popout footer.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Quick add</h4>
<p>The popout footer has a quick-add input. Whatever you type is saved as
a new comment under the current course code, instantly available the
next time you open the library.</p>

<h4>System defaults &amp; the proposal workflow</h4>
<p>Managers with <code>local/unifiedgrader:managesystemdefaults</code> curate
a site-wide set of default tags and comments at <em>Site administration →
Plugins → Local plugins → Unified Grader → Manage comment library</em>. These
appear to every teacher with a star badge and are read-only for them.</p>

<p>Teachers can <strong>suggest</strong> one of their own comments for promotion
to a system default via the star icon on the comment card (an optional
rationale is prompted). What happens next depends on the
<code>require_systemdefault_approval</code> admin setting:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>On (default):</strong> the suggestion queues under <em>Pending submissions</em> on the admin page. A manager approves it (creating a system-default copy that preserves system tags and leaves the teacher's original untouched) or rejects it with an optional reason. The teacher's card shows a <em>Pending review</em> badge until decided, then a <em>Rejected</em> badge (reason on hover) if declined.</li>
    <li><strong>Off:</strong> the suggestion is promoted to a system default immediately, inheriting only system tags; the proposal is still recorded for audit.</li>
</ul>
</section>

{{! ----- Notes ----- }}
<section id="feature-notes">
<h3>Teacher notes (private)</h3>

<p>A note is private to the teacher who wrote it but visible to other
teachers with the <code>local/unifiedgrader:viewnotes</code> capability —
useful for moderation handoffs and "remember to follow up" reminders.</p>

<p>Notes are not surfaced to students under any circumstance.
Capabilities default to teacher / editingteacher / manager only.</p>

<p>Notes appear in the marking panel under a <em>Notes</em> heading.
Each note shows the author and timestamp; only the author can edit or
delete their own. Notes don't sync to the gradebook — they are purely
internal communication.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Submission comments ----- }}
<section id="feature-submission-comments">
<h3>Submission comments (chat-style)</h3>

<p>An optional messenger-style comments thread between the teacher and
the student, gated by the admin setting <code>enable_submission_comments</code>.</p>

<ul>
    <li>For <strong>assignments</strong>, the widget replaces Moodle's core submission comments inline on the student assignment view.</li>
    <li>For <strong>quizzes / forums / BBB</strong>, a non-intrusive chat-bubble icon appears in the activity-information region; click to open the thread.</li>
    <li>Notifications are sent on new comments via Moodle's standard messaging API (<code>db/messages.php</code>).</li>
</ul>

<p>Comments are stored in <code>local_unifiedgrader_scomm</code> and
remain accessible after grading is finalised.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Grade input, clearing & resets ----- }}
<section id="feature-grades">
<h3>Grade input, clearing &amp; resets</h3>

<p>The overall grade box takes a plain number, and also understands two dash
shortcuts that mirror how Moodle's gradebook lets you clear a cell.</p>

<h4>Entering a grade</h4>
<ul>
    <li>Type the mark directly, or let a marking guide / rubric compute it. A live percentage shows next to the field.</li>
    <li>The value is <strong>capped at the activity's maximum mark</strong> — typing 40 in a 20-mark assignment shows an inline error and refuses to save (the server rejects it too, as belt-and-braces). Over-100% / extra-credit marks aren't supported. Scale grading uses a dropdown that can't exceed, and quiz marks are clamped by the question engine instead.</li>
    <li>A comma decimal separator is accepted (<code>3,5</code> becomes <code>3.5</code>) so markers in comma-decimal locales round-trip correctly.</li>
</ul>

<h4><code>-</code> — clear the grade ("no grade")</h4>
<p>Typing a single <code>-</code> in the grade box <strong>resets the grade to
"no grade"</strong> — the same gesture Moodle's gradebook accepts to empty a
cell. The field clears immediately, any manual-override lock drops, and the save
sends a "no grade" value to the server. The student reverts to ungraded (and
re-appears under the <em>Ungraded</em> filter). Feedback, annotations, and the
submission itself are untouched — only the numeric grade is removed. (Any other
non-numeric stray input is normalised the same way rather than erroring.)</p>

<h4><code>--</code> — deliberate reset</h4>
<p>Typing a double <code>--</code> does everything <code>-</code> does, plus two
clean-up steps for recovering from a messy gradebook state:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Removes an orphan submission row</strong> whose status isn't <code>submitted</code> — i.e. one created by accidental teacher interaction with the marking panel, never a real student submission. Genuinely submitted work is left intact.</li>
    <li><strong>Lifts a stuck gradebook override.</strong> It clears the <code>grade_grades.overridden</code> flag, so a column pinned to a previously-applied value (typically from <code>gradepenalty_duedate</code> or a manual gradebook edit) reverts to genuinely ungraded rather than staying frozen at the old number.</li>
</ul>
<p>Both shortcuts behave the same for <strong>forums</strong> as for
assignments, and never touch the student's posts or submission content.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Penalties ----- }}
<section id="feature-penalties">
<h3>Penalties</h3>

<p>Two kinds of grade penalty are supported:</p>

<ol>
    <li><strong>Late penalty</strong> via the <code>gradepenalty_duedate</code> plugin — automatic, based on configured rules. Applied when the gradebook receives the grade. The raw teacher-entered grade is kept in the activity's grade table; only the gradebook value is reduced.</li>
    <li><strong>Manual penalty</strong> entered by the marker — wordcount-based, custom-labelled, or arbitrary percentage. Stored in <code>local_unifiedgrader_penalty</code>; subtracted from the gradebook value the same way.</li>
</ol>

<p>Penalties show as badges in the marking panel header. Click a badge
to open the penalty details popout, where you can add, edit, or remove
manual penalties.</p>

<p>When any penalty is active and a grade has been entered, a <em>Final grade
after penalties</em> line shows the net mark and percentage below the badges,
so you can see the value the gradebook will store without opening the gradebook.
The automatic <code>-X% Late</code> badge is derived from the activity's
effective due date and the student's actual <em>submit</em> time (not draft-start
time), so it stays visible for already-graded submissions — a returning marker
or moderator can see at a glance that the saved grade was reduced.</p>

<p>For <strong>scale-based grading</strong>, manual penalties are hidden
(percentage deductions don't make sense on a discrete scale).</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Academic-integrity referral ----- }}
<section id="feature-referral">
<h3>Academic-integrity referral</h3>

<p>When a marker decides a submission must be escalated for an
academic-integrity / plagiarism review, they can <strong>flag it for
review</strong> straight from the marking panel. Gated by the
<code>local/unifiedgrader:refer</code> capability.</p>

<h4>What the flag does</h4>
<ul>
    <li>Records an <strong>open referral</strong> for the student on this activity (one open referral per student + activity; clicking again reuses the existing open row rather than stacking duplicates).</li>
    <li><strong>Pauses the grading-turnaround clock.</strong> Consumers such as the CoIFish reports read the open status and stop counting turnaround time while the review is pending, so the marker isn't penalised for the review delay.</li>
    <li>Once open, the control shows a <em>Referred for integrity review</em> badge with a <em>Mark resolved</em> affordance. Resolving records an outcome (cleared / upheld) and the resolution time.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Where the button lives</h4>
<p>The action is logically part of the plagiarism report, so <strong>whenever a
plagiarism card is shown</strong> for the submission the single button is hosted
there, below the file shields. When there is no plagiarism card (no plagiarism
plugin produced a result), the button appears in the grade card instead. You
never see it in two places at once.</p>

<h4>Behaviour with and without a report form</h4>
<ul>
    <li><strong>With a report form configured</strong> (<code>enable_report_form</code> + <code>report_form_url</code>): the button reads <em>Report academic impropriety</em>. A single click flags the submission <em>and</em> opens the prefilled report form in a new tab — guarded by a confirmation so an accidental click can be cancelled. (See <a href="#plugin-plagiarism">Plagiarism plugins</a> for the form's placeholder URL.)</li>
    <li><strong>Without a report form:</strong> the button reads <em>Refer for integrity review</em> and opens a short note field — the note is recorded with the referral, and confirming flags it.</li>
</ul>

<p>Markers who can open the report form but lack the <code>refer</code>
capability still get a plain <em>Report academic impropriety</em> link in the
plagiarism card — they get the form, just not the flag.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Overrides & extensions ----- }}
<section id="feature-overrides">
<h3>Overrides &amp; extensions</h3>

<p>Each adapter exposes the override / extension surface the underlying
activity supports:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Assignment</strong>: user overrides (open / close / cut-off date), extensions, with auto-adjusting cut-off when an extension exceeds it.</li>
    <li><strong>Quiz</strong>: native <code>quiz_overrides</code> rows, plus <code>quizaccess_duedate</code> extensions when that plugin is installed.</li>
    <li><strong>Forum</strong>: plugin-owned forum extensions (<code>local_unifiedgrader_fext</code>) — Moodle core forums don't have a native extension table.</li>
    <li><strong>BigBlueButton</strong>: no overrides / extensions (BBB has no per-user due dates).</li>
</ul>

<p>The <em>Overrides &amp; extensions</em> modal in the marking panel
header surfaces all of the above through one form, regardless of activity
type. A <em>Clear all</em> action removes overrides and extensions for the
current student in one shot.</p>

<p>Granting an extension <em>after</em> the student has been graded
opens a confirmation dialog asking whether to recalculate the late
penalty — this avoids the "ghost penalty" pattern where a granted
extension didn't propagate to the gradebook.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Marking guides & rubrics ----- }}
<section id="feature-rubrics">
<h3>Marking guides &amp; rubrics</h3>

<p>Both grading methods render in the marking pane:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Marking guide</strong> — per-criterion score input + remark textarea + max-score badge + comment-library button.</li>
    <li><strong>Rubric</strong> — per-criterion level buttons (one per defined level), click to select.</li>
</ul>

<p>The card supports both <em>simple grade override</em> (when admin
allows) and computed totals from criteria. Switching activity types is
seamless — assignment / forum / quiz / BBB-via-<code>bbbext_advgrd</code>
all flow through the same code path.</p>

<h4>Score validation &amp; rounding</h4>
<p>Marking-guide criterion scores are validated against the criterion's
allocated maximum: a negative value, or one above the cap, flags inline with a
red border and a <em>"Score for "X" must be between 0 and Y"</em> message, and
autosave / manual save refuse to fire while any criterion is flagged. The same
widget and validation drive per-question marks in quiz manual grading. The total
badge is rounded at source to the gradebook item's configured decimal places
(with a floor of 2dp), so it never shows floating-point artefacts like
<code>13.899999999999999&nbsp;/&nbsp;25</code>.</p>

<h4>Override indicator</h4>
<p>When the displayed grade differs from what the rubric / marking guide
computes — because a marker typed a manual override (allowed by
<code>allow_manual_grade_override</code>) — a yellow <em>Overridden</em> badge
appears below the grade input, showing the rubric total and a <em>Reset to
rubric total</em> link. The badge persists across sessions, so a returning
marker or moderator immediately sees the score was hand-adjusted; clicking
<em>Reset</em> re-syncs the input to the rubric value and autosaves. Once a
marker edits the top-level grade, subsequent rubric edits no longer overwrite it
(the lock clears on student switch), and the override is autosaved on focus-out.</p>

<h4>Save lifecycle (race protection)</h4>
<p>Auto-save fires after a 1.5 s debounce when focus leaves the rubric
body. Without protection, the post-save state refresh would arrive while
the teacher is still typing and would clobber in-flight keystrokes.</p>

<p>The plugin avoids this with <strong>incremental DOM updates</strong>:</p>

<ul>
    <li><code>_handleSaveGrade</code> snapshots the values being sent into <code>_lastSentScores</code> / <code>_lastSentRemarks</code> / <code>_lastSentRubricSelections</code>.</li>
    <li>When the post-save refresh arrives, <code>_renderGuide</code> / <code>_renderRubric</code> compare each field's in-memory value to the snapshot.</li>
    <li>Fields that match the snapshot get the server's value (clean update).</li>
    <li>Fields where the value has diverged — meaning the teacher has typed since the save fired — are <em>preserved</em>, and the form is re-marked dirty so the next focusout catches up.</li>
    <li>The currently-focused field is never clobbered.</li>
</ul>

<p>The rebuild-from-scratch path still runs on first render and when the
criteria definition itself has changed (e.g. switching to a different
student). For everything else, only values are updated; input elements
are not destroyed.</p>

<div class="local-unifiedgrader-help-screenshot">
    <i class="fa fa-image" aria-hidden="true"></i>
    <span>Screenshot: marking guide with three criteria, each showing max badge,
    score input with autosave indicator, remark textarea, and a comment-library
    icon button.</span>
</div>
</section>

{{! ----- Group mode ----- }}
<section id="feature-groups">
<h3>Group mode</h3>

<p>The student navigator's group selector supports Moodle's standard
group modes (<em>No groups</em>, <em>Separate groups</em>, <em>Visible
groups</em>). When the teacher belongs to multiple groups, an
<em>"All my groups"</em> pseudo-option fans out to a multi-select
checkbox dropdown.</p>

<p>By default the selector opens on the teacher's <em>own</em> group(s) rather
than "All groups" — "All my groups" when they belong to several, the specific
group when they belong to one — and this now applies to course managers and
admins too, not just capability-restricted users. The choice is remembered per
activity (keyed by course-module) so it survives refreshes and revisits.</p>

<p>Filtering is delegated to each adapter — the adapter knows how to
intersect its native participant set with the active group filter.</p>

<p>Group / team submissions in mod_assign show the team representative
once; saving a grade cascades to all team members per Moodle's standard
behaviour.</p>
</section>

{{! ----- Auto-save ----- }}
<section id="feature-autosave">
<h3>Auto-save &amp; offline cache</h3>

<p>Every editable field is tracked by a <em>DirtyTracker</em>:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Edits mark the field dirty and update the save indicator.</li>
    <li>Focus-out triggers a 1.5 s debounce timer.</li>
    <li>When the timer fires, a save is dispatched via the standard <code>local_unifiedgrader_save_grade</code> web service.</li>
    <li>While a save is in flight, no second save can fire (prevents stale data overwriting fresh).</li>
</ul>

<h4>Offline cache</h4>
<p>An IndexedDB-backed cache stores in-progress edits per
<code>(cmid, userid, field)</code>. If the network drops:</p>

<ul>
    <li>The save is queued and retried automatically when the connection comes back.</li>
    <li>The save indicator shows <em>Offline — saved locally</em>.</li>
    <li>On next page load, recovered unsaved changes are offered as a banner; the teacher can <em>Restore</em> or <em>Discard</em>.</li>
</ul>

<h4>Save before navigating</h4>
<p>The student navigator dispatches an <code>unifiedgrader:requestsave</code>
event before switching students, giving the marking panel a chance to
flush in-progress saves so they target the correct student.</p>

<figure class="local-unifiedgrader-help-figure my-4">
